                    <div class="card">
                        <div class="card-body">
                            <h1 class="card-title">Appendix 1</h1>
                            <p>
                                <i>
                                    Extract (partial) from the Firm’s Quality Management Manual – Categories of Risk (paragraph 8.14 to 8.15)
                                    <br><br>
                                    The firm classifies its engagements into four categories namely: -
                                    <br><br>
                                    &nbsp;&nbsp;a)  High risk engagement requiring full scope review by the safeguard reviewer (H1)
                                    <br><br>
                                    &nbsp;&nbsp;b)  High risk engagement requiring focused review on the modified opinion or a specific area(s) by the safeguard reviewer (H2)
                                    <br><br>
                                    &nbsp;&nbsp;c)  Moderate risk engagement may require areas to be subjected to focused or selective review by safeguard reviewer based on engagement partner’s discretion (M)
                                    <br><br>
                                    &nbsp;&nbsp;d)  Normal risk engagement requiring no safeguard review (N)
                                    <br><br>
                                    A safeguard review is an objective evaluation of the significant judgements made by the engagement team and the conclusions reached in formulating the report before the report is issued. The firm typically requires safeguard reviews for all the following “high risk” engagements:
                                    <br><br>
                                    (A “high risk” client that is rated as H1, is a client considered to be of high public interest or likely to be subject to higher levels of scrutiny for a variety of reasons.)
                                    <br><br>
                                    &nbsp;&nbsp;1.	Transnational entities (which include some of the categories below) (Note it is only necessary to apply the safeguard review requirement for a subsidiary if it is greater than 15% of the group by turnover, gross assets or audit hours);
                                    <br><br>
                                    &nbsp;&nbsp;2.	Publicly traded or listed companies;
                                    <br><br>
                                    &nbsp;&nbsp;3.	Large charities with donation income of S$10 million or more;
                                    <br><br>
                                    &nbsp;&nbsp;4.	Other public interest entities, such as banks, financial institutions, insurance entities, large pension schemes, large publicly funded charities (with donation in excess of S$10 million), and regulated fund management activities including if their financial statements are likely to be used across national boundaries (i.e., internationally) or if they are important National Institutions;
                                    <br><br>
                                    &nbsp;&nbsp;5.	“For sale” entities or those which are known to be targets for acquisition by another entity;
                                    <br><br>
                                    &nbsp;&nbsp;6.	Entities where a qualified audit report was issued in the last financial statements, or where a qualified audit report is expected to be issued in the current financial statements which is not due to a technical qualification such as those falling under H2;
                                    <br><br>
                                    &nbsp;&nbsp;7.	Entities where there are particular reporting difficulties where there may be doubts over the nature of audit report to be issued.
                                    <br><br>
                                    &nbsp;&nbsp;8.	First year audit of a new client arising from a change of auditors (unless the engagement is non-complex and straight-forward in nature which based on the engagement partner recommendation does not need a safeguard review).
                                    <br><br>
                                    &nbsp;&nbsp;9.	Any other significant concerns identified by the engagement partner that requires a safeguard review under H1.
                                    <br><br>
                                    The Firm classifies high risk engagements into two types namely H1 and H2.
                                    <br><br><br>
                                    <h3 class="card-title">H1 engagements</h3>
                                    For engagements such as those listed from (1) to (9) above, the firm classifies these engagements as High risk 1 (“H1”).
                                    <br><br>
                                    <h3 class="card-title">H2 engagements</h3>
                                    However, there are certain specific instances where the engagement is not really a “high risk” engagement simply because the entity incurred losses and has deficit in shareholder’s equity as the share capital is only S$2 and the funding is entirely by way of loans from the holding/related companies and there are no borrowings from third parties.  So long as the holding company provides the financial support and there is no risk of borrowings from third parties, there is no real risk of going concern. Thus, the modification of the audit report on going concern which is commonly the case with this type of engagement represents a technical modification and would not require a full scope review.
                                    Another specific instance would be the non-consolidation of a subsidiary by the Singapore holding company as the ultimate parent does not publish consolidated accounts that are publicly available. Again, this type of engagement is not really a high-risk engagement and the reason is commonly one of cost and benefit to the holding company which does not need the group accounts at the Singapore level.
                                    For those engagements as described above, they are classified as High risk 2 (“H2”). Such engagements will require only the modified opinion to be reviewed by the safeguard reviewer including the documentation of the matters that give rise to the modified opinion. Based on the judgement of the safeguard reviewer, he or she can extend the review to other areas on a selective basis as he or she deems necessary after discussion with the engagement partner or manager.
                                </i>
                            </p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>
    </main><!-- End #main -->
</div>
